This notebook shows examples of how public holiday features affect model predictions. Additionally, it provides prediction explanations in the form of shapley values. Here we examine 3 models:

  • a baseline model that has date, sales aggregates, and pv features
  • a model with date, sales aggregates, pv features, and public holidays (original or old)
  • a model with date, sales aggregates, pv features, and public holidays (new encoded features)

We examine 5 holidays in 2019:

  • Christmas
  • Easter
  • Christy Himmelfahrt
  • National Tag
  • Pfingsten

For this example analysis we only took 4 items 200063, 200036, 200031, and 200066

The presentation of analiysis always sticks to the same pattern

  • present 2 charts with sales in 2018 and 2019
  • 2 tables with uplift figures on 2018 and 2019
  • 2 shapley value charts with prediction explanations of the model with original public holiday features. First one explains prediction on a day right before the holiday and the second one right after the holiday
  • 2 shapley value charts with prediction explanations of the model with new public holiday features. First one explains prediction on a day right before the holiday and the second one right after the holiday
  • 3 RMSE values for the baseline, baseline + orig. public holidays, baseline + new public holidays
  • 4 charts: baseline prediction and actual sales, baseline + orig. holidays and actual sales, baseline + new public holidays and actual sales, everything in one

bars_b = alt.Chart(christmas_old.expl_b).mark_bar().encode(
    x='shap_value:Q',
    y=alt.Y(
        'feature:N',
        sort=alt.EncodingSortField(
            field="shap_value",  # The field to use for the sort
            order="descending"  # The order to sort in
        )
    ),
    color=alt.condition(
        alt.datum.shap_value > 0,
        alt.value("steelblue"),  # The positive color
        alt.value("orange")  # The negative color
    )
)
text_b = bars_b.mark_text(
    align='left',
    baseline='middle',
    dx=3  # Nudges text to right so it doesn't appear on top of the bar
).encode(
    text='shap_value:Q',
       color=alt.condition(
        alt.datum.shap_value > 0,
        alt.value("steelblue"),  # The positive color
        alt.value("red")  # The negative color
    )
)

        'feature:N',
        sort=alt.EncodingSortField(
            field="shap_value",  # The field to use for the sort
            order="descending"  # The order to sort in
        )

    color=alt.condition(
